title: For Sale:  Webley & Scott Vintage WWII Mark IV Flare Gun / Pistol
postcontent: Vintage WWII British / Canadian forces used these Webley & Scott Mark IV Flare Gun / Pistols. $200 o.b.o Zinc coated, 37mm, 5 1/2" barrel, trigger action works, beautiful patina, very rare and hard to find. These guns were made about 1939 in Australia for British forces during WWII. This one comes with a Vintage carved Pine or Cedar wood box that it was found in. The handle is cracked and chipped, but otherwise it is in firing condition. I was only able to find one other of these for sale online and it was in similar condition. This is a great item for the Vintage / Antique gun collector or WWII / Military collector. Here is some more info: Webley & Scott produced a number of single-shot, break open signal flare gun devices used by Commonwealth Military Forces during the First and Second World Wars. Perhaps the most prolific of these was the No.1 MkIII, produced in 1918 at the company's Birmingham facility. A variant, differing only in its use of black plastic grip panels instead of the earlier wood, was produced by Colonial Sugar Refinery in Sydney, Australia in 1942. The pistols can often be seen in films, notably Lawrence of Arabia, where the title character discharges one to signal the beginning of an attack on a disabled enemy train, and The Empire Strikes Back where bounty hunter Boba Fett is seen carrying one as a rifle. title: For Sale/Trade:  Egyptian Hakim 8mm Battle Rifle
postcontent:
I have an Hakim 8mm semi-auto battle rifle I might be interested in trading for the right offer. Looking for unique firearms that I couldn't go out and find locally.

Internals/metal are in good shape. Bolt functions like it should, and there has been no cutting or bubba type shenanigans anywhere. This gun is stock.
The wood has some dings in it, but they're minor and could be cleaned up if someone was so inclined. I didn't want to alter this rifle in any way, so I haven't tried.

These were made in the 50's and 60's by Egypt using machines that originally made the Swedish AG-42, which is similar in action but a different caliber.
These rifles were some of the first direct impingement battle rifles. Only 70,000 or so were ever made, and of that only a couple thousand were imported into the US. They have an adjustable gas system, excellent muzzle break, and are fed by 10 round detachable box magazines.

The bore is PRISTINE and it shoots straight as an arrow. Took it out recently and put about 60 rounds of Yugo FMJ through it and it ran flawlessly.
Have a couple boxes of ammo still on clips to go with it.

Any other questions, just ask.

title: For Sale:  VERY Custom Armalite M-15 Carbine
postcontent:
Some people stick a rail, fore grip, and red dot on their gun and figure they’re all set, but I think the devil’s in the details; I pretty much swapped out everything that was worth changing. Check out the list and you’ll see what I mean, and note the prices and you’ll understand what a lot of folks stop after just changing the hand guards. I sold a bunch of odds & ends in another ad, and I hate to see this go, but I have another AR-15 project coming and something’s gotta give. 

Armalite M15 Lower Receiver Assembly (P/N# L15PCB, $335.00). Forged 7075-T6 Hard Anodized aluminum receiver with Manganese Phosphate steel finish, a two stage tactical trigger ($100.00), a mil-spec 6-position receiver extension (aka buffer tube), a standard buffer & buffer spring, a Choate Machine & Tool QD Ambi Sling Loop Mount with QD swivel ($40.00), a Magpul MOE Enhanced Trigger Guard (green polymer, $9.00), a Battle Arms Development Inc. modular Ambidextrous Safety Selector (aka “B.A.D.A.S.S.” with extra heads, $75.00), a Magpul B.A.D. Lever (aka Battery Assist Device, $30.00), a Patriot Ordnance Factory Ambi-Catch magazine release lever (NSN 1005-01-537-6498, $90.00), a set of KNS Stainless Steel Anti-Rotation Hammer/Trigger Pins (P/N# KNS-1154K, $30.00), an over-size magazine release button ($15.00), and over-size take-down pins ($25.00). Total invested: $750.00

Armalite M15/A4 Flattop Upper Receiver Assembly (P/N# EK0130A, $190.00). Forged 7075-T6 Hard Anodized aluminum receiver with Manganese Phosphate steel finish. Has complete bolt carrier group, forward assist,  a aluminum charging handle with a Badger Ordinance Gen II tactical latch ($25.00), and a laser etched aftermarket dust cover with “Infidel” in Arabic and advancing American flag (as the US Army patch, $20.00). Also includes an Army issue MATECH Folding AR15 BUIS Sight (NSN 1005-01-484-8000, P/N 12996812, $90.00). Total invested: $325.00

Armalite heavy-profile 16 inch barrel: This is a mid-length with the barrel extension & ramps, has RH 1/9 twist, chrome-lined, not drilled for a pinned A2 sight base (also has no 203 notch) ($250.00), YHM Front Flip Sight Tower, Hooded gas block with sling attachment and bayonet lug (YHM-9394-H, $95.00), and a standard “bird cage” flash suppressor. Total invested: $345.00

Yankee Hill Machine Mid-length Lightweight Forearm (YHM-9634, $135.00). Free-float style and includes a Forearm End Cap (YHM-9484-A, $20.00), Forearm Plug Kit (YHM-9437K, $10.00), and QD sling attachment with push-button QD swivel ($25.00). Total invested: $190.00

Command Arms/CAA/Mako stock set: Includes a green UPG16 adjustable grip with green and extra black inserts ($45.00), a black UPGS target stand ($15.00), a green CBSM six position stock ($70.00), a black PRFCS side rail ($15.00), a black ACP adjustable cheek piece ($30.00), a green Mako MWG magwell grip ($25.00), and a Mako T-Pod combined fore grip and bipod ($135.00). Total invested: $335.00

So altogether, and not counting the shipping charges I paid, I’ve got just over $1900.00 in this rifle. I honestly can’t tell you how many hours I spent putting this together, finding & ordering stuff (plus S&H charges), but it was well worth effort because of how it came out. I don’t even want to guess what you’d pay to have one built even close to this, although I showed it to an employee at a local gun shop and they thought I must have $3000 to $3500 in it. I originally intended to put in a 20” heavy 6.8 SPC barrel and try some 500 to 600 yard stuff with it, but even with a crappy 3x9 40mm scope I have put mil-surp 5.56 on paper at just over 400 meters as it is. It’s definitely been used, but way less than 500 rounds, and except for a few scuffs and dinks, it’s in great shape. I wouldn’t hesitate to carry this rifle into any situation and stake my life and family on it. It comes just as you see it, with a black nylon Bulldog case, two Magpul 20 round PMAGs (with pull assists & covers), and a set of UTG rubber rail covers too (never got around to getting green ones since I was gonna use a YHM smooth forearm on the 6.8 and wouldn’t need any), a sling, plus a bag of original parts & spares, the manual & paperwork, etc. Show me an ID, hand me the cash, pick up some ammo on the way and you’ll be good for the range.

Please feel free to ask questions, and I do have more pictures, but make me an offer. It’s gotta go, so seriously it’s “Or Best Offer”, I’d rather do it here and not fool with shipping on some other site. Email is OK, but I prefer you call or text REDACTED. You really gotta see this one. Thanks, Tommy
